article.headline: Kraayeveld hits five 3-pointers
article.linkText: Ducks upset No. 10 LSU behind Kraayeveld's 26
article.story:
EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- The Oregon Ducks quickly found out how they
stack up against the rest of the country.

In only their second game of the season, the unranked and
unheralded Ducks took a lead in the second minute and convincingly
beat No. 9 Louisiana State 76-67 in Sunday's championship game of
the Women's Sports Foundation Classic.

Cathrine Kraayeveld scored 26 points and Andrea Bills added 21
as the Ducks (2-0) beat a Top 10 team for the first time in three
years.

"It is very early and we recognize that," Oregon coach Bev
Smith said. "Still, it's not so much what we did as how we did
it."

Seimone Augustus led LSU (1-1) with 22 points.

Kraayeveld hit five 3-pointers, finishing 9-for-20 from the
field, and added nine rebounds. Corrie Mizusawa had 12 points.

Kraayeveld scored 17 of her points in the first half, including
a 3-pointer at 6:05 to put Oregon up 30-14.

The Tigers were never able to get into a rhythm on offense,
shooting 29.7 percent in the first half.

LSU closed to 63-54 with four minutes left after a 6-0 run, but
Bills followed with a three-point play to rebuild the lead.

"We've set the tone of how were going to play the rest of the
season," said Kraayeveld, a senior forward who missed 13 games
last season with a staph infection in her right knee as the Ducks
finished 12-16.

"We're going to keep going and look to get better from here on
out."

The Ducks last defeated a Top-10 team in January 2000, when they
beat UCLA 67-58. They last beat a team from the Southeastern
Conference in 1981 -- a 63-59 win against LSU.

"They came out with fire and intensity and they fought hard the
whole game," Augustus said. "They took advantage of every mistake
we made, every turnover, and turned around and made something
special out of it."
